    Scope and Contents
The Harmony Brothers, the founders of Springfield's "first Rock and Roll band," discuss their musical career in the 1950s.  With a sound similar to the more well-known Everly Brothers, the brothers became local favorites with a fan club and performed at local clubs, televisions station music shows, and Uncle Tom's Barn Dance in Decatur.  They discuss playing at a "Splatter Platter Party" in St. Louis with other artists such as Jerry Lee Lewis, Carl Mann, Dee Clark, and the Jesters.  They also recall performing with Annette Funicello.5 CDs, 180 mins., 74 pp.
Interview by Chris Reynolds, 2006
